description.value: A complete pottery amphora of Samian style a made in a coarse red silt fabric, with a small foot and rounded shoulder. The sides expand from the foot to the shoulder, then converge to a narrow, cylindrical neck, which is finished with a rounded, external rim. At either side of the neck is a loop-handle, extending from the neck to the shoulder. The fabric comtains much grit, especially small particles of quartz and flint. There are remains of a pale cream-yellow slip on the body, especially on the lower part. No doubt it once covered the whole vessel but much has been lost due to flaking of the surface, which shows visible evidence of lamination.

The exterior was covered by a pale slip, which varies from cream to pink in colour in different areas, but much of this slip has disappeared owing to exfoliation of the surface. In applying the handles to the neck too much pressure was exerted, with the result that the neck was deformed to an eliptical shape instead of a circle.
